merican Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in East Yorkshire called Cave, apparently from a river name derived from Old English <i>cāf</i> ‘swift’.","English (of Norman origin): nickname from Norman and Picard Old French <i>cauf</i> (from Latin <i>calvus</i>) ‘bald’.","French: topographic name for someone who lived in or near a cave, from Old French <i>cave</i> ‘cave’, ‘cellar’ (from Latin <i>cavea</i>, a derivative of <i>cavus</i> ‘hollow’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Cavin","meanings":["Scottish (Wigtownshire): variant of <b>Caveen</b>, a shortened form of Manx <i>Mac Dhaimhín</i>, son of <i>Daimhín</i>. The personal name is a diminutive of Gaelic <i>damh</i> ‘bard, poet’.","French: diminutive of   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Caves","meanings":["English: variant of   Cave  , with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>."]},{"name":"Keeve","meanings":["English: perhaps a variant of   Cave  . This surname is rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Chaffee","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): descriptive nickname from a derivative of Old French <i>chauf</i> ‘bald’ (from Latin <i>calvus</i>). Compare   Cave  ."]},{"name":"Cavett","meanings":["Scottish (of French origin): altered form of French <b>Cavet</b>, which is either a diminutive of   Cave   3 or a metonymic occupational name for a laborer, one who used a <i>cavet</i>, an Old Occitan word for a tool for clearing ground for cultivation."]}]},{"name":"Joyce","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Apparently from the Norman male name <i>Josce</i> (Middle English <i>Josse</i>), which in turn is from <i>Jodocus</i>, a Latinized form of a Breton name, <i>Iodoc</i>, meaning ‘lord’, borne by a 7th-century Breton saint. The name was in use in England among Breton followers of William the Conqueror. However, although this was fairly common as a male given name in the Middle Ages, it had virtually died out by the 14th century. There is evidence of its use as a girl's name from the 16th century onwards in parishes with strong Puritan links, which suggests that it may have been associated with the vocabulary word <i>joy</i>;  see  Joy .  It was strongly revived in the 19th century under the influence of popular fiction. It is borne by characters in Mrs  Henry Wood's  East Lynne (  1861 ) and  Edna Lyall's  In the Golden Days (  1885 ). Modern use may well have been influenced also by the common Irish surname derived from the medieval Norman male name.  See also  Joss ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705189,"age":29,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":60,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705191,"age":85,"year":"1315","toYear":"1317","julianDay":2201354,"title":"Famine Strikes Europe","description":"A famine caused by cold winters and wet summers across Europe caused millions to die due to starvation. Desperation from hunger caused high levels of crime, stampedes in bread lines in London, infanticide, and even cannibalism throughout Europe.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705192,"age":98,"year":"1328","julianDay":2206102,"title":"First War of Scottish Independence","description":"The First War of Scottish Independence began after England invaded Scotland in 1296. The Treaty of Edinburgh was signed in 1328 which declared peace between the two kingdoms and brought the war to an end.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705193,"age":107,"year":"1337","toYear":"1453","j